an%20interview%20helped%20her%20land%20a%20job.%20%3Cp%3ENatalie%20Keyssar%20for%20BI%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EAllyson%20Noonan%2C%2039%2C%20is%20a%20PR%20consultant%20and%20adjunct%20professor%20based%20in%20New%20York.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20graduated%20from%20Marymount%20Manhattan%20College%20in%20December%202007%20with%20a%20degree%20in%20communication%20arts.%20I%20hoped%20to%20land%20a%20public%20relations%20role.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20I%20had%20excellent%20internships%2C%20no%20one%20was%20hiring%20when%20the%20recession%20started.%20While%20I%20was%20job%20searching%2C%20I%20worked%20part-time%20at%20Anthropologie%20and%20babysat.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20submitting%20more%20than%20100%20applications%2C%20I%20still%20couldn't%20find%20work.%20But%20then%2C%20someone%20who%20interviewed%20me%20for%20a%20job%20I%20didn't%20get%20contacted%20me%2C%20saying%20she%20had%20a%20friend%20in%20the%20industry%20looking%20for%20an%20entry-level%20position%20that%20she%20thought%20I'd%20be%20a%20fit%20for.%20This%20position%20turned%20out%20to%20be%20my%20first%20full-time%20job%20at%20a%20PR%20agency%2C%20which%20I%20started%20in%20June%202008.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20experience%20taught%20me%20that%20it's%20wise%20to%20take%20every%20interview%20you%20can%20%E2%80%94%20even%20if%20you're%20not%20sure%20it's%20a%20good%20fit.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20first%20position%20was%20definitely%20not%20my%20dream%20job.%20The%20company%20focused%20on%20an%20industry%20I%20wasn't%20especially%20interested%20in%2C%20and%20I%20had%20to%20accept%20a%20salary%20that%20was%20much%20lower%20than%20my%20peers%20who%20graduated%20just%20a%20couple%20of%20years%20before%20me.%20However%2C%20I%20learned%20the%20foundational%20PR%20skills%20that%20have%20served%20me%20well%20ever%20since.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2251e9469a-5875-467a-b725-fb73a951e6af%5C%22%3EYour%20first%20job%20doesn't%20have%20to%20be%20your%20dream%20job%20%E2%80%94%20or%20even%20related%20to%20your%20career%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EAlicia%20Strata%2C%2038%2C%20is%20a%20marketing%20director%20at%20a%20luxury%20travel%20agency%20based%20in%20Alabama.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20graduated%20from%20Columbia%20College%20Chicago%20in%20May%202010%20with%20a%20marketing%20communications%20degree.%20I%20hoped%20to%20land%20an%20internship%20that%20would%20help%20me%20get%20a%20job%20at%20an%20advertising%20agency%2C%20but%20the%20job%20market%20was%20tough.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDuring%20the%20second%20semester%20of%20my%20senior%20year%2C%20I%20decided%20to%20apply%20to%20Teach%20For%20America%20and%20was%20accepted.%20Teaching%20was%20completely%20out%20of%20my%20area%20of%20study%2C%20but%20I%20was%20looking%20for%20something%20that%20felt%20both%20purposeful%20and%20possible%20in%20a%20shrinking%20job%20market.%20TFA%20offered%20that%3A%20a%20paycheck%2C%20a%20mission%2C%20and%20structure%20during%20chaos.%20The%20summer%20after%20graduation%2C%20I%20moved%20to%20South%20Dakota%20to%20begin%20my%20placement%20as%20a%204th-grade%20teacher.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAlthough%20TFA%20didn't%20directly%20further%20my%20marketing%20career%2C%20it%20did%20give%20me%20valuable%20leadership%20skills%20and%20life%20experience%20that%20a%20traditional%20path%20wouldn't%20have%20afforded%20me.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20biggest%20advice%20for%20new%20college%20grads%20is%20that%20you%20don't%20have%20to%20start%20in%20your%20dream%20job%2C%20but%20you%20do%20have%20to%20start.%20Take%20whatever%20you%20can%20to%20get%20going%2C%20but%20keep%20your%20eyes%20open%20and%20continue%20to%20pursue%20what%20you%20really%20want.%20That's%20what%20eventually%20led%20me%20back%20to%20marketing.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22f5abedfc-a339-4472-a360-190b065fa9e4%5C%22%3ELooking%20for%20a%20job%20is%20a%20job%20in%20itself%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%226126%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Kourtney%20Jason%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.ins